import java.io.*;   // Import the Java File I/O package, so we can use it later in our program: `File` object is created using this class java_48499_FileScanner_A01 specifying path of files or directories to read from and write into file system at a given location . It also provides methods such as openInputStream( ) , closeOutputStream()  etc
import java.util.*; // Import the Java Util package, so we can use it later in our program: `List` object is created using this class for storing multiple items of any type (like List<String> or Map < K , V >) . It also provides methods such as add( ), remove( ) etc
 
public static void main_FileScannerExample(){   //Start Program Execution point from the `main` method. Main Method is automatically run when program starts executing and it's equivalent to a standalone Java application 'Main'. In this case, we will not call function here but only use as reference for other methods
  File file = new java.io.File("D:\\"); // Initializes the `file` object with given path D:\ in real world scenarios you can pass any directory and it's sub directories to search files too (i.e., if want all .txt from specific folder then provide that location)
  List<String> fileList = new ArrayList<>();   /// Creates a list of String for storing the names(fileNames). This is similar as `ArrayList` in Java but with type information, so you can use methods like add(), remove() etc. only when these types are provided (like we did here)
  try {    // Try block to wrap our code inside it if any error occur then this will handle exception and print the stack trace for debugging purpose    
      FileScannerExample(file, fileList);   /// Call method with `File` object as input parameter. It is equivalent of calling your function in C/C++ or Java where you pass a value to another program using call by reference concept (i.e., pointer). Also it's the entry point for this example
  } catch(Exception e) {   // If an exception occur then print that on console, if any error occurs when running our code in IDE and also while executing from command line terminal or system shell with 'java FileScannerExample', we will go here to handle those exceptions (catch block where you can put your logic for handling specific type of Exception)
      System.out.println("An exception has occurred: " + e);   // Print the error details when an unexpected occurs during execution 
	  }    /// End Try-Catch Block, it is like 'try' and catch'. It handles any exceptions that occur while our program runs (like if there was file not found or directory unaccessible etc.) with a specific message. Also you can use more detailed exception handling in real world scenarios based on your project requirement 
 }   /// End main method of the Java Application Programming, which will be equivalent to `main` function when compiled as standalone application and it's entry point for execution from command line terminal or system shell (i.e., how you call a java class program)    '''